data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. `Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 (`SYSLIB0006`). The fix is cooperative cancellation with `CancellationTokenSource`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async version
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // caller cancelled — propagate as-is
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(work)` | Uses the thread pool; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `Task.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` | Cancellation-aware waiting (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) | Cooperative cancellation replaces forced abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | The exception type thrown by cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed — cancellation is cooperative |
| Manual `Exception error` capture | `Task` propagates exceptions | `Task.Run` marshals exceptions automatically |

## Key Pitfalls

1. **Work doesn't magically stop.** Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work()` is a long CPU-bound operation that never checks the token, the task keeps running after timeout — you just stop waiting. To truly cancel, pass the token into `work`:
   ```csharp
   public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
   {
       using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
       return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                  .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                  .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
   }
   ```
   Then check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside loops.

2. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It uses internal timers. Always wrap in `using` to avoid leaks.

3. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** Use the `when` filter to distinguish timeout vs. external cancellation — only convert timeout to `TimeoutException`.

4. **Blocking I/O won't be interrupted.** If `work()` calls `socket.Receive()` or similar, cancellation can't interrupt it. Switch to async I/O overloads that accept `CancellationToken`.

5. **Uncooperative third-party code.** If you *must* forcibly kill work that can't accept a token, move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` — that's the only .NET 8 equivalent of hard termination.
